3. Code Example
Please not that in the code, when we retrieve character from the string or pattern, we need to use s[i-1] and p[j-1] instead of s[i] and p[j] as the index of the string and pattern is 0-based.
from collections import defaultdict
class Solution:
    def isMatch(self,s, p):
        m, n = len(s), len(p)
        dp = [[False] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
     # DP is a table with m+1 rows and n+1 columns
     # we retrieve dp[i][k], i is the index of s, k is the index of p
        dp[0][0] = True
        for j in range(2,n+1):
            if p[j-1]=='*':
                dp[0][j]=dp[0][j-2]

        for i in range(1, m + 1):
            for j in range(1, n + 1):
                if p[j-1] == '*':
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2] # zero occurrence
                    if s[i-1]==p[j-2] or p[j-2]=='.':
                        dp[i][j]|=dp[i-1][j] or dp[i-1][j-2] # one or more occurrence
                else:
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] and (s[i-1] == p[j-1] or p[j-1] == '.')
        return dp[m][n]

sum along axis 2
When axis(dim) is 2, given each element in this dimension is the elements of the matrix, so the sum is the sum of the elements.
\[
\begin{array}{c|c}
\begin{bmatrix}
1+2+3,4+5+6
\end{bmatrix} &
\begin{bmatrix}
7+8+9,10+11+12
\end{bmatrix}
\end{array}
\]
so the result is:
array([[6, 15], [24, 33]])
Aso, when axis(dim) is -1, it means the operation is performed along the last dimension. So for 2d array, axis -1 is the same as axis 1.
